WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:07.300
So the moment comes where we have to
present all of this back to the client.

2
00:00:07.300 --> 00:00:12.386
Now we've been involving them as we go,
so that kinda helps to some degree.

3
00:00:12.386 --> 00:00:17.292
But we need to get sooner or later to a
point where we do a probably a more formal

4
00:00:17.292 --> 00:00:21.836
presentation of some description and
get some more formal feedback.

5
00:00:21.836 --> 00:00:28.661
So first of all, take the time to
prepare before presenting, right?

6
00:00:28.661 --> 00:00:33.728
You want everything to be all lined
up before you get to any kind

7
00:00:33.728 --> 00:00:38.417
of formal presentation process
when it comes to design.

8
00:00:38.417 --> 00:00:43.724
And the more thoroughly you're prepared,
the better the whole thing is gonna go.

9
00:00:43.724 --> 00:00:50.132
So for a start, it's gonna give you more
confidence when it comes to presenting.

10
00:00:50.132 --> 00:00:53.782
And if you're more confident,
that tends to give the client and

11
00:00:53.782 --> 00:00:56.360
stakeholders a lot more
confidence as well.

12
00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:02.636
Preparation will also prevent you from
being surprised by any questions or

13
00:01:02.636 --> 00:01:05.260
objections from stakeholders.

14
00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:09.800
So thinking through what they might come
back with is a key part of preparing.

15
00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:14.630
And having a plan, right, means that
you're gonna remain in control of

16
00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:19.303
the process because very quickly
when it comes to presenting design,

17
00:01:19.303 --> 00:01:21.694
you can really lose control there.

18
00:01:21.694 --> 00:01:25.237
And it kind of, everybody else
starts designing the website and

19
00:01:25.237 --> 00:01:28.714
you become a pixel pusher that
just moves a few things around and

20
00:01:28.714 --> 00:01:30.496
that's a horrible place to be.

21
00:01:30.496 --> 00:01:32.280
So we're gonna want to avoid that as well.

22
00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:36.680
So one way of preparing
as we've already said,

23
00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.086
is to involve the stakeholder
at multiple times.

24
00:01:40.086 --> 00:01:44.970
With the style tiles, with working out
the content and the objections and

25
00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:47.898
the brand keywords, and the wireframing.

26
00:01:47.898 --> 00:01:51.893
All of those are opportunities to
engage with the stakeholder and

27
00:01:51.893 --> 00:01:55.897
get them involved and by doing that,
they will understand more.

28
00:01:55.897 --> 00:01:59.093
Because the stakeholder is more
involved in the design process,

29
00:01:59.093 --> 00:02:02.593
they'll understand the decisions
that have been made along the line.

30
00:02:02.593 --> 00:02:07.459
And that puts them in a much better place
to make educated and informed decisions.

31
00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:14.890
Secondly, right, it will give them a sense
of ownership over the design, right?

32
00:02:14.890 --> 00:02:18.069
They will feel like they were
a part of creating it and

33
00:02:18.069 --> 00:02:22.854
if they were a part of creating it,
they're gonna be less likely to reject it.

34
00:02:22.854 --> 00:02:28.353
And finally, if they were involved in
creating it, they're also gonna be more

35
00:02:28.353 --> 00:02:33.869
likely to defend that design and that
approach to other stakeholders, right?

36
00:02:33.869 --> 00:02:36.370
So involving people is really powerful.

37
00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:38.936
Just to briefly remind
you how we're doing that,

38
00:02:38.936 --> 00:02:41.879
we're gonna get them involved
in defining the content.

39
00:02:41.879 --> 00:02:44.988
We're gonna get them involved in
prioritizing the content with user

40
00:02:44.988 --> 00:02:46.281
retention point exercise.

41
00:02:46.281 --> 00:02:51.220
Creating brand keywords and
in the style guides, right?

42
00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:55.582
Those are our key opportunities but there
are whole other opportunities as well.

43
00:02:55.582 --> 00:03:01.906
For example, I do exercises like the book
jacket exercise where I get them

44
00:03:01.906 --> 00:03:07.312
to imagine that they are representing
their company on a book.

45
00:03:07.312 --> 00:03:10.341
And they have to make decisions
about what goes on the front cover,

46
00:03:10.341 --> 00:03:13.604
what goes on the spine, what goes on
the back cover and the inside flap.

47
00:03:13.604 --> 00:03:18.285
And all of that helps them to
prioritize their messaging and

48
00:03:18.285 --> 00:03:23.071
things like their value proposition and
that kind of stuff.

49
00:03:23.071 --> 00:03:26.489
Another exercise I sometimes do
is called the six-up exercise.

50
00:03:26.489 --> 00:03:31.829
One of the big problems when it comes to
websites is that people have a particular

51
00:03:31.829 --> 00:03:36.863
mental image in their heads of what
the website will do and how it will work.

52
00:03:36.863 --> 00:03:40.193
And one of the things that you need
to do is show them well actually,

53
00:03:40.193 --> 00:03:42.637
that's not the only way
it could have been done.

54
00:03:42.637 --> 00:03:47.007
So what we do is we take a single sheet of
paper, we fold it in thirds one way, and

55
00:03:47.007 --> 00:03:51.850
half the others so you end up with six
boxes basically on your sheet of paper.

56
00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:55.618
And you ask them to sketch out in
the first box how they imagined

57
00:03:55.618 --> 00:03:59.940
a particular page or
function will work on the website.

58
00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:04.016
Once they've done that, you then say okay,
now fill in the other five, right?

59
00:04:04.016 --> 00:04:08.177
And that forces them to think in different
ways that you might be able to solve

60
00:04:08.177 --> 00:04:09.228
the same problem.

61
00:04:09.228 --> 00:04:12.533
That can be a really useful
group exercise as well.

62
00:04:12.533 --> 00:04:17.528
So there's an article there
of a few different exercises

63
00:04:17.528 --> 00:04:21.072
you can do to engage your stakeholders.

64
00:04:21.072 --> 00:04:25.969
So that's fundamentally how you wanna
prepare, is by getting them involved,

65
00:04:25.969 --> 00:04:27.513
that's a big part of it.

66
00:04:27.513 --> 00:04:30.990
But then, you also need to think
about possible objections.

67
00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:34.805
Now I talked about objections earlier
in the context of user objections,

68
00:04:34.805 --> 00:04:38.249
why users might not act on a website,
might not download your app,

69
00:04:38.249 --> 00:04:41.270
might not do your call to action,
whatever it be.

70
00:04:41.270 --> 00:04:41.886
But now,

71
00:04:41.886 --> 00:04:47.510
I'm talking about objections about why
people might reject your design, right?

72
00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:51.480
So why stakeholders might go no,
this design isn't right.

73
00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:56.661
So the chances are that you will be
able to make some educated guesses about

74
00:04:56.661 --> 00:05:02.859
problems or changes that your stakeholder
might raise during a presentation, right?

75
00:05:02.859 --> 00:05:07.863
I highly encourage you,
just to spend a couple of minutes

76
00:05:07.863 --> 00:05:12.867
writing down a list of these
things that they might say and

77
00:05:12.867 --> 00:05:20.499
how you might answer them, so that you're
not surprised during the meeting, right?

78
00:05:20.499 --> 00:05:25.988
Because if you have to think on your
feet in the meeting, it can be really

79
00:05:25.988 --> 00:05:31.580
quite hard to do and having those
lined up makes an enormous difference.

80
00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:34.411
So let's look at some common
ones that come up and

81
00:05:34.411 --> 00:05:38.920
how I would respond to them, just to give
you a taste of what I've got in mind.

82
00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:44.257
One that comes up all the time is can
we move it above the fold, all right?

83
00:05:44.257 --> 00:05:49.631
Really common thing that comes up so
I have this little patter that whenever

84
00:05:49.631 --> 00:05:54.680
that comes up, just flips, it clicks
in and I just say the same thing.

85
00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:59.398
Which is basically, it's actually
an understandable misconception that users

86
00:05:59.398 --> 00:06:03.102
don't scroll and so
you need prominent content above the fold.

87
00:06:03.102 --> 00:06:06.163
And actually,
that misconception is based on some

88
00:06:06.163 --> 00:06:11.380
research done in 1994 by Jacob Nielsen
that said, users don't scroll.

89
00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:12.547
So that has stuck and

90
00:06:12.547 --> 00:06:17.225
everybody now believes everything has to
be above the fold, if you want it seen.

91
00:06:17.225 --> 00:06:22.972
However, as early as 1998, Jacob Nielsen
actually updated his study to say well,

92
00:06:22.972 --> 00:06:26.170
that's no longer a problem and
users do scroll.

